<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,323,1259]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
External morphology: 
<taxonomicName authority=": Massively" authorityName="Massively" box="[461,801,767,791]" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Iophon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Porifera" rank="subSpecies" species="situ" subSpecies="appearance">
<emphasis box="[461,679,768,791]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">In situ appearance:</emphasis>
Massively
</taxonomicName>
thickly encrusting sponge with the surface rising up into one or more mounds. Specimens very variable in size but can be quite large with diameters of greater than 
<quantity box="[1367,1432,803,827]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="cm" value="30.0">30cm</quantity>
. Sponge encrusting on bedrock and are frequently overgrown by ascidians and bryozoans. Surface covered with large pore sieves (up to 
<quantity box="[442,511,875,899]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5cm</quantity>
in diameter) and large, irregularly scattered, oscules, which can reach 
<quantity box="[1354,1403,875,899]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="cm" value="2.0">2cm</quantity>
in diameter, are present. Sponge white to peach in colour but with a patchily dark chocolate brown surface layer present in some specimens, possibly formed of algae. The pore sieves often have a slightly lighter rim than the main sponge body. (
<figureCitation box="[377,473,983,1007]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-410@22.[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). a) In situ appearance specimen Mc7687, scale bar 10cm; b) Skeleton Mc7689, ectosome to top, scale bar 500µm; Spicules Mc7689 c) acanthostyle, scale bar 100µm, d) ectosomal oxea, scale bar 100µm, e) chelae, scale bar 10µm." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 12a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,323,1259]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,477,1019,1043]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Preserved appearance:</emphasis>
Firm but compressible grey sponge with pore sieves clearly visible on the tough ectosomal layer.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,323,1259]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,307,1090,1115]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Skeleton:</emphasis>
Choanosomal skeleton composed of a basal layer of acanthostyles from which thick ascending columns of up to 20 oxea ascend. Acanthostyles echinate the lower parts of these columns. In the ectosome the ends of the columns of oxea fan out to form a continuous surface layer. Chelae are very abundant and scattered throughout tissue (
<figureCitation box="[360,458,1199,1223]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-410@22.[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). a) In situ appearance specimen Mc7687, scale bar 10cm; b) Skeleton Mc7689, ectosome to top, scale bar 500µm; Spicules Mc7689 c) acanthostyle, scale bar 100µm, d) ectosomal oxea, scale bar 100µm, e) chelae, scale bar 10µm." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 12b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,323,1259]" box="[199,644,1234,1259]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Spicules:</emphasis>
Measurements from Mc7689.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="22" pageNumber="23" startId="22.[151,250,1923,1946]" targetBox="[151,1436,1315,1903]" targetPageId="22">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1923,2007]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,1923,1946]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">FIGURE 12.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Topsent, 1917)" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[300,695,1924,1946]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Phorbas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="glaberrimus">
<emphasis box="[300,519,1924,1946]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Phorbas glaberrimus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Topsent, E." box="[535,688,1924,1946]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref31918" refString="Topsent, E. (1917) Spongiaires. In: Joubin, L. (Ed.), Deuxieme Expedition Antarctique Francaise (1908 - 1910) Commandee par le Dr. Jean Charcot. Sciences Physiques: Documents Scientifiques. Masson &amp; Cie, Paris, pp. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1917">Topsent, 1917</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. a) 
<taxonomicName box="[737,927,1925,1946]" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Iophon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="22" pageNumber="41" phylum="Porifera" rank="subSpecies" species="situ" subSpecies="appearance">
<emphasis box="[737,804,1925,1946]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">In situ</emphasis>
appearance
</taxonomicName>
specimen Mc7687, scale bar 10cm; b) Skeleton Mc7689, ectosome to top, scale bar 500µm; Spicules Mc7689 c) acanthostyle, scale bar 100µm, d) ectosomal oxea, scale bar 100µm, e) chelae, scale bar 10µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,716]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,151,176]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Acanthostyles:</emphasis>
216(264)313 by 9.5(14.1)19.7µm. Parallel sided with an abrupt point. Head not tylote. Strongly spined along whole length (
<figureCitation box="[564,660,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-410@22.[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). a) In situ appearance specimen Mc7687, scale bar 10cm; b) Skeleton Mc7689, ectosome to top, scale bar 500µm; Spicules Mc7689 c) acanthostyle, scale bar 100µm, d) ectosomal oxea, scale bar 100µm, e) chelae, scale bar 10µm." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 12c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,716]" box="[199,1230,223,248]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,394,224,248]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Ectosomal oxea:</emphasis>
365(428)476 by 9.9(13.0)17.9µm. Fusiform with abrupt points (
<figureCitation box="[1120,1218,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-410@22.[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). a) In situ appearance specimen Mc7687, scale bar 10cm; b) Skeleton Mc7689, ectosome to top, scale bar 500µm; Spicules Mc7689 c) acanthostyle, scale bar 100µm, d) ectosomal oxea, scale bar 100µm, e) chelae, scale bar 10µm." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 12d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,716]" box="[199,626,259,284]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,290,259,284]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Chelae:</emphasis>
18.9(22.4)25.4µm (
<figureCitation box="[516,613,260,284]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-410@22.[151,1436,1315,1903]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Phorbas glaberrimus (Topsent, 1917). a) In situ appearance specimen Mc7687, scale bar 10cm; b) Skeleton Mc7689, ectosome to top, scale bar 500µm; Spicules Mc7689 c) acanthostyle, scale bar 100µm, d) ectosomal oxea, scale bar 100µm, e) chelae, scale bar 10µm." pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 12e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,716]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Remarks: 
<taxonomicName authority="(Topsent, 1917)" baseAuthorityName="Topsent" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[315,726,295,320]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Phorbas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="glaberrimus">
<emphasis box="[315,548,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Phorbas glaberrimus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Topsent, E." box="[561,718,295,319]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref31918" refString="Topsent, E. (1917) Spongiaires. In: Joubin, L. (Ed.), Deuxieme Expedition Antarctique Francaise (1908 - 1910) Commandee par le Dr. Jean Charcot. Sciences Physiques: Documents Scientifiques. Masson &amp; Cie, Paris, pp. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1917">Topsent, 1917</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
was originally described from 
<quantity box="[1064,1126,295,319]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9699999999999998" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="297.0">297m</quantity>
in the Antarctic and appears to be a good match for these specimens, although Topsent reports slightly larger oxea (530–600 by 20–22µm). 
<bibRefCitation author="Rios, P." pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 527" refId="ref30759" refString="Rios, P. (2006) Esponjas del orden Poecilosclerida de las campanas espanolas de bentos Antartico. Unpublished PhD Thesis, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, pp. 1 - 527." type="book chapter" year="2006">Rios (2006)</bibRefCitation>
reports smaller oxea of 420–590µm, more similar to the range in our specimens, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Koltun, V. M." box="[1164,1320,367,391]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1955 - 1958" refId="ref29786" refString="Koltun, V. M. (1964) Sponges of the Antarctic I. Tetraxonida and Cornacuspongida. In: Pavilovskii, E. P., Andriyashev, A. P. &amp; Ushakov, P. V., (Eds.), Biological reports of the Soviet Antarctic expedition (1955 - 1958). Volume 2. Akademya Nauk SSSR, Moscow, Leningrad, pp. 6 - 133." type="book chapter" year="1964">Koltun (1964)</bibRefCitation>
also gives a wider range (382–600µm). 
<bibRefCitation author="Rios, P." box="[485,619,404,428]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 527" refId="ref30759" refString="Rios, P. (2006) Esponjas del orden Poecilosclerida de las campanas espanolas de bentos Antartico. Unpublished PhD Thesis, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, pp. 1 - 527." type="book chapter" year="2006">Rios (2006)</bibRefCitation>
reports two categories of acanthostyles (200–260 and 300–350µm), the acanthostyles of Mc7689 could be sub-divided into two length categories 216–233µm and 271–313µm but this division is not apparent in the other specimens and not obvious when viewed down the microscope.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,151,716]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,348,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Distribution:</emphasis>
This species is widely distributed in the Antarctic: Alexander I land (
<bibRefCitation author="Topsent, E." box="[1135,1292,511,535]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref31918" refString="Topsent, E. (1917) Spongiaires. In: Joubin, L. (Ed.), Deuxieme Expedition Antarctique Francaise (1908 - 1910) Commandee par le Dr. Jean Charcot. Sciences Physiques: Documents Scientifiques. Masson &amp; Cie, Paris, pp. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1917">Topsent 1917</bibRefCitation>
), Wilheim II coast, Banzare coast, Wilkes Land, Victoria Land, Princess Astrid Coast (
<bibRefCitation author="Koltun, V. M." box="[1021,1171,548,572]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1955 - 1958" refId="ref29786" refString="Koltun, V. M. (1964) Sponges of the Antarctic I. Tetraxonida and Cornacuspongida. In: Pavilovskii, E. P., Andriyashev, A. P. &amp; Ushakov, P. V., (Eds.), Biological reports of the Soviet Antarctic expedition (1955 - 1958). Volume 2. Akademya Nauk SSSR, Moscow, Leningrad, pp. 6 - 133." type="book chapter" year="1964">Koltun 1964</bibRefCitation>
), MacRobertson Coast (
<bibRefCitation author="Koltun, V. M." box="[158,307,583,607]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="163 - 198" refId="ref29922" refString="Koltun, V. M. (1976) Porifera - Part 1: Antarctic Sponges. Report B. A. N. Z. Antarctic Research Expedition 1929 - 1931 (B, Zoology and Botany), 5, 163 - 198." type="journal article" year="1976">Koltun 1976</bibRefCitation>
), Weddell Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Barthel, D. &amp; Tendal, O. S. &amp; Panzer, K." box="[489,711,583,608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="120 - 131" refId="ref27808" refString="Barthel, D., Tendal, O. S. &amp; Panzer, K. (1990) Ecology and taxonomy of sponges in the eastern Weddell Sea shelf and slope communities. Reports on polar research, 68, 120 - 131." type="journal article" year="1990">
Barthel 
<emphasis box="[583,642,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al.</emphasis>
1990
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gutt, J. &amp; Koltun, V. M." box="[725,981,583,607]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="227 - 234" refId="ref29325" refString="Gutt, J. &amp; Koltun, V. M. (1995) Sponges of the Lazarev and Weddell Sea, Antarctica: explanations for their patchy occurrence. Antarctic Science, 7, 227 - 234." type="journal article" year="1995">Gutt and Koltun 1995</bibRefCitation>
), Ross Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Pansini, M. &amp; Calcinai, B. &amp; Cattaneo-Vietti, R. &amp; Sara, M." box="[1126,1348,583,608]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="67 - 100" refId="ref30470" refString="Pansini, M., Calcinai, B., Cattaneo-Vietti, R. &amp; Sara, M. (1994) Demosponges from Terra Nova Bay (Ross Sea, Antarctica): 1987 / 1988 and 1989 / 90. Programma Nazionale di Ricerche in Antartide, Expeditions. National Scientific Commission for Antarctica Oceanographic Campaign 1987 / 88 and 1989 / 90, 3, 67 - 100." type="journal article" year="1994">
Pansini 
<emphasis box="[1220,1279,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al.</emphasis>
1994
</bibRefCitation>
), South 
<collectingCountry box="[151,321,620,644]" name="Trinidad Island" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Trinidad Island</collectingCountry>
and Bransfield Strait (
<bibRefCitation author="Rios, P." box="[575,693,620,644]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 527" refId="ref30759" refString="Rios, P. (2006) Esponjas del orden Poecilosclerida de las campanas espanolas de bentos Antartico. Unpublished PhD Thesis, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, pp. 1 - 527." type="book chapter" year="2006">Rios 2006</bibRefCitation>
) from depths 
<quantity box="[850,973,620,644]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.3" metricValueMax="13.7" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="m" value="730.0" valueMax="1370.0" valueMin="90.0">90–1370m</quantity>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Burton, M." box="[984,1143,620,644]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="393 - 458" refId="ref28052" refString="Burton, M. (1929) British Antarctic (' Terra Nova') Expedition, 1910. Natural History Report. Porifera: Part II: Antarctic Sponges. Zoology, 6, 393 - 458." type="journal article" year="1929">Burton (1929)</bibRefCitation>
also erroneously reported it as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ridley and Dendy, 1886)" baseAuthorityName="Ridley and Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[361,955,655,680]" class="Demospongiae" family="Dendoricellidae" genus="Pyloderma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="latrunculioides">
<emphasis box="[361,660,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Pyloderma latrunculioides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ridley, S. O. &amp; Dendy, A." box="[674,947,655,679]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="325 - 351" refId="ref30671" refString="Ridley, S. O. &amp; Dendy, A. (1886) Preliminary Report on the Monaxonida collected by H. M. S. &quot; Challenger &quot;. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 18, 325 - 351." type="journal article" year="1886">Ridley and Dendy, 1886</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Antarctic but it is not clear which of his specimens are this species. There are no previous published records from 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1212,692,716]" name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">South Georgia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
